{{Redirect-distinguish|Maji language|Majhi language}} {{Infobox language |name=Dizin |states=[[Ethiopia]] |speakers={{sigfig|33900|2}} |ref=<ref>[http://www.csa.gov.et/images/documents/pdf_files/regional/CountryLevel.pdf Ethiopia 2007 Census]</ref> |date=2007 census |familycolor=Afro-Asiatic |fam2=[[Omotic languages|Omotic]] |fam3=[[North Omotic languages|North]] |fam4=[[Dizoid languages|Dizoid]] |iso3=mdx |glotto=dizi1235 |glottorefname=Dizin }}
'''Dizin''' (often called “Dizi” or “Maji” in the literature) is an [[Omotic languages|Omotic language]] of the [[Afro-Asiatic languages|Afro-Asiatic]] language family spoken by the [[Dizi people]], primarily in the [[Maji (woreda)|Maji]] [[woreda]] of the [[Southern Nations, Nationalities and Peoples Region]], located in southwestern [[Ethiopia]].<ref>[http://www.csa.gov.et/images/documents/pdf_files/regional/SNNPR1.pdf ''The 1994 Population and Housing census of the SNNPR Region: Volume I, Part I''], Table 2.15. According to Table 2.16, Dizin is second to Amharic in the number of speakers in the woreda's towns of [[Maji, Ethiopia|Maji]], [[Jeba, Ethiopia|Jeba]] and [[Tum, Ethiopia|Tum]].</ref> The 2007 census listed 33,927 speakers.<ref>[http://www.csa.gov.et/images/documents/pdf_files/regional/CountryLevel.pdf Ethiopia 2007 Census]</ref> A population of 17,583 was identified as monolinguals in 1994.<ref>Raymond G. Gordon Jr., ed. 2005. ''Ethnologue: Languages of the World''. 15th edition. Dallas: Summer Institute of Linguistics.</ref>
The language has basic [[subject–object–verb|SOV]] (subject–object–verb) word order, tones, and is largely suffixing. Phonologically, "Features of the Dizin sound system include [[Glottalic consonant|glottalized]] consonants, [[syllabic nasal]]s, [[lengthened vowel]]s, three [[phonemic tone]] levels and [[contour tone]]s. Western Dizin has phonemic retroflex consonants. The glottal stop is analyzed as phonemic word initially before nasals, but not phonemic elsewhere". (Beachy 2005:iv)
Dizin, together with the [[Sheko language|Sheko]] and [[Nayi language|Nayi]] languages, is part of a cluster of languages variously called "Maji" or "Dizoid".
