{{Infobox language family |name=Ijoid |region=Southern [[Nigeria]] |familycolor=Niger-Congo |child1=[[Ijo languages|Ijaw]] |child2=?[[Defaka language|Defaka]] |glotto=ijoi1239 |glottorefname=Ijoid |family=[[Niger–Congo]]?}}
'''Ijoid''' is a proposed but undemonstrated group of languages linking the [[Ijaw languages]] (Ịjọ) with the endangered [[Defaka language]]. The similarities, however, may be due to Ijaw influence on Defaka.<ref>Roger Blench, [http://www.rogerblench.info/Language/Niger-Congo/General/Niger-Congo%20an%20alternative%20view.pdf Niger-Congo: an alternative view]</ref>
The Ijoid, or perhaps just Ijaw, languages form a divergent branch of the [[Niger–Congo languages|Niger–Congo family]] and are noted for their [[subject–object–verb]] basic word order, which is otherwise an unusual feature in Niger–Congo, shared only by such distant branches as [[Mande languages|Mande]] and [[Dogon languages|Dogon]]. Like Mande and Dogon, Ijoid lacks even traces of the [[noun class]] system considered characteristic of Niger–Congo, and so may have split early from that family. Linguist Gerrit Dimmendaal doubts its inclusion in Niger–Congo altogether and considers the Ijaw/Ijoid languages to be an independent family.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0U4k9duWUOIC|title=Historical Linguistics and the Comparative Study of African Languages|last=Dimmendaal|first=Gerrit Jan|date=2011-01-01|publisher=John Benjamins Publishing|isbn=9027211787|language=en}}</ref> <ref>{{cite article|url=https://www.academia.edu/29429826/Joseph_Greenberg_and_the_Current_State_of_Niger-Congo|title=Joseph Greenberg and the Current State of Niger-Congo|last=Babaev|first=Kirill}}</ref>
