{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}} {{Use British English|date=October 2016}} {{Infobox person | name = Sonia Edwards | image = | image_size = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = | birth_place = [[Cemaes]] | death_date = | death_place = | death_cause = | residence = | other_names = | known_for = | education = | employer = | occupation = | title = | salary = | networth = | height = | weight = | term = | predecessor = | successor = | party = | boards = | religion = | spouse = | partner = | children = | parents = | relatives = | signature = | website = | footnotes = | nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]] }} '''Sonia Edwards''' is a [[British people|British]] poet and writer who writes primarily in Welsh.
==Life== Edwards was born in [[Cemaes]] on the island of [[Anglesey]]. She is known as a writer of books in Welsh although she also translates her own books into English. She won the Arts Council Book of the Year Award in 1996. In 1999 she won the Prose Medal at the National Eisteddfod on Anglesey.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.ylolfa.com/chwilio.php?lang=cy&func=pori_awdur&awdur=Sonia%20Edwards| title=Sonia Edwards| publisher=Y Lolfa|language=cy|access-date=10 August 2017}}</ref> In 2017 she won it again at the Anglesey Eisteddfod.
She taught Welsh at [[Ysgol Gyfun Llangefni]], a school in [[Llangefni]] on the same island where she was born. She retired from teaching to pursue a career in writing.
==Works== *''Nofelau Nawr: Cadwyn O Flodau'', 2000<ref name=gomer>[http://www.gomer.co.uk/index.php/catalogsearch/result/?q=sonia Sonia Edwards], Gomer Press</ref> *''White Tree'', 2001 *''A White Veil for Tomorrow'', 2003 *''Swigod: Jelygaid'', 2012<ref name=gomer/> *''Rhannu Ymbarèl'', 2017
